(232, 7, '2015-06-13 19:56:04', '2015-06-13 14:26:04', '<img class=" aligncenter" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/6b/DaVinciCode.jpg" alt="" width="320" height="479" />\r\n\r\nDan Brown in all his books emphasizes that all information, artworks and facts stated in his books are true. While for many years, I blindly believed this statement, recently I decided to do a background check at the legitimacy of this statement. Although initially everything seemed well in place, I slowly started stumbling upon factual errors and wrong information being sold to the public. Taking for granted that a majority of the readers will not know much about the backgrounds of the works, Dan Brown added mysterious societies and strange rituals which appealed to the audience, even more so because the audience mostly if not wholly believed that the these societies and rituals existed. I however felt a little cheated for being made to believe something that is not true and hence I would like to bring out a few factual errors in what is considered Dan Brown’s best work, The Da Vinci Code.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Priory of Sion:</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAccording to the book, the Priory of Sion is an ancient organization connected to Goddess worship. Dan Brown writes that the organization was founded in 1099 and it was named after the Biblical Mount Zion. The truth is however very different. The Priory of Sion was actually founded in1956 by Pierre Plantard, Andre Bonhomme and others and was named after a mountain in France.\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li><strong><em>Opus Dei</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe book claims that the Opus Dei is a monastic order which is the Pope’s ‘personal prelature’. Silas the murderer is said to be an Opus Dei monk who uses a cilice to flagellate himself and receives very deep wounds. Factually Opus Dei has no monks and Dan Brown greatly exaggerates the effects of voluntary mortification of flesh as the kind of wounds described in the book cannot be caused from a normal cilice.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Rosslyn Chapel</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe Chapel is a major feature in the last part of the novel, though many incorrect assertions were made about the structure. The book states that the Chapel was built by the Knights Templar, and contains a six-pointed Star of David worn into the stone floor although such star has never been seen in the floor. Also the chapel was founded by William Sinclair, 1st Earl of Caithness of the Scoto-Norman Sinclair family and not by the Knights Templar\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone" src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcR6KbQasx634TE8fmh9Y0XugyTcl0LNAVPcupet5a7eq9-8aM0U" alt="" width="259" height="194" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Vatican</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIn the story, the Vatican is said to be the center of power in the early Catholic Church. It is said that that there is a reference to the Vatican in the Gnostic Writings of the 4<sup>th</sup> century. However it was not until the 15<sup>th</sup> century that there was anything like official power in the vicinity of the Vatican Hill in Rome. In the 4<sup>th</sup> century all that existed of the Vatican was a little more than a church and cemetery by the side of the road. Also the book claims that St. Peter’s is a cathedral, although Saint Peter’s is more of a church technically.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n	<li><strong><em>Geography</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe book’s storyline that the “Albino Monk” was arrested in France, imprisoned in Andorra and escaped to Spain, demonstrates the lack of basic research that would be gleaned from a quick glance at a map or tourist guide. It is improbable that someone arrested along the French coast would be imprisoned in another country (in this case Andorra which is a different jurisdiction and several hundred kilometers away up in the Pyrenean Mountains). After the scene in the Temple Church, London, the heroes of the story take the tube from Temple Station to King’s College. In fact King’s College is nearer to the Temple Church than to Temple Station, and any tube journey would have carried them further away from King’s College. Brown also states “The chapel’s geographic coordinates fall precisely on the north-south meridian that runs through Glastonbury”. This statement is incorrect: Rosslyn Chapel lies more towards the east-west meridian. Brown appears to have confused geographic north with magnetic north.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://i.infopls.com/images/Europemap-2010.gif" alt="" width="713" height="535" />\r\n\r\nIt is not just the The Da Vinci Code. All of Dan Brown’s works have major factual fallacies, which have been introduced to take advantage of the fact that any mysterious object gains much more interest if it is rendered to be factually correct. As far as the story is concerned, the suspense, the thrill, the build-up, everything is very well put and the book has all the ingredients to make an interesting read, however keeping the factual inaccuracies in mind, my outlook of the book has changed from “A must read book, filled with well researched information which provides an insight into history along with an interesting storyline” to “Just another historical fiction thriller”.', 'The Da Vinci Code: Of Facts or Fallacies?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-da-vinci-code-of-facts-or-fallacies', '', '', '2015-06-13 19:56:52', '2015-06-13 14:26:52', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=232', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(247, 1, '2015-06-24 19:45:03', '2015-06-24 14:15:03', '"Hero or Villain?" is a frequent question that acts as conversation starter in social circles and people usually prefer the villain. It is a bit surprising, to say the least, that people would deliberately choose a character that is portrayed as vindictive, resentful and even criminal over someone who is amiable and righteous.\r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\nA memorable tale is always determined by its plot and more importantly, its characters. A thrilling chemistry between the antagonist and protagonist that leaves the audience at the edge of their seats is sure to be a blockbuster or a bestseller. But the best stories that are a class apart are those with a well-defined villain.\r\nSure, ultimately the hero saves the day but it''s the villain that steals the show. Here are a few reasons why the hated are really the most loved.\r\n\r\n1. There would be no story without a villain.\r\n\r\nOne can only appreciate the light once you see the darkness. A hero''s ''pristine nature'' can be shown if has a plan to foil and an anti-hero to defeat. They are rivals yet complementary to each other and a perfect plot.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://i.ytimg.com/vi/0_mEDo0D7f4/hqdefault.jpg" alt="" width="311" height="233" />\r\n\r\n2. An engrossing back story.\r\n\r\nBehind their devilish schemes, heinous intentions and hardened personalities, lie a hundred secrets why villains turned into monsters.\r\n\r\nTake for example, Bill the Butcher (or William Cutting), the antagonist in Gangs of New York. Inspired by real life gangster William Poole, Bill was a violent man hell-bent on revenge against immigrants who were responsible for his father''s death. He was known for his moral code, his patriotism and sense of honour. Today he is famously remembered for his last words, "Thank God... I died a true American."\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.monologuedb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/daniel-day-lewis-bill-the-butcher-cutting-gangs-of-new-york.jpg" alt="" width="462" height="308" />\r\n\r\nHeathcliff (Wuthering Heights), an iconic villain in English literature is a character still yet to be fully understood even after a century of his existence. Born as a homeless orphan but sheltered and mentored by Mr. Earnshaw, Heathcliff, Heathcliff falls in love with Catherine Earnshaw who betrays their love and marries Edgar Linton, a man of better social and economic background. In a rage of vengeance and sadness, Heathcliff becomes a living nightmare in a gentleman''s disguise.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://36.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lnnalzPlNN1qe5f96o1_1280.jpg" alt="" width="411" height="274" />\r\n\r\n3. Honestly, they''re smarter.\r\n\r\nThere''s nothing more appealing than cunning intellect and a cunning intellect is a villain''s forte.\r\n\r\nLight Yagami (Death Note) could control death and the supernatural.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/scale_super/1/11495/240324-73255-light-yagami.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="225" />\r\n\r\nMister Sinister (X-Men), a scientific genius could alter his human genome to be invulnerable and ageless. Also he resuscitated Apocalypse, carrier of the first mutant X-gene. That''s pretty damn smart.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/original/11113/111133725/3864874-1.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="301" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMrs. Eleanor Iselin (The Manchurian Candidate) is a ruthless Communist agent who plans to take over America. Her cold blooded and domineering attitude towards even her husband and son and her ambition to succeed makes her one of the smartest villains of all time.\r\n\r\n<strong><img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.morethings.com/fan/manchurian_candidate/plot-revealed-angela_lansbury-laurence_harvey09.jpg" alt="" width="440" height="222" /></strong>\r\n\r\n4. People are attracted to imperfections.\r\n\r\nEveryone wants to be perfect but we''re not. Heroes on paper and screens are the closest depiction to perfection. They represent goodwill, selflessness and struggle. They represent silver linings.\r\n\r\nVillains are a realistic portrayal of mankind''s flaws, exaggerations of man''s sins. They are greedy (Shylock), ambitious (Macbeth), broken (Voldemort), vengeful (Maleficent) and desirable (Jennifer in Jennifer''s Body). There is raw, crass and unabashed emotion in a villain which makes a story all the more better. In the real world, there is no black and white but shades of grey.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class="" src="http://img4.wikia.nocookie.net/__cb20120727155045/disney/images/5/5e/Puzzle-clementoni-disney-villains-panorama-1000-p-CLM39088.5-0.jpg" alt="" width="756" height="272" />\r\n\r\n5. We cling to the hope that they might change sides.\r\n\r\nContinuing from the previous point, we truly want to believe that a villain has a human heart and even though tortured can seek redemption,\r\n\r\nDr. Gru from the Despicable Me series is a classic example. From conniving to steal the moon to become a doting father of three is a complete and delightful change of character.\r\n\r\nMaybe Claude Frollo (The Hunchback of Notre Dame) could find it in his otherwise compassionate heart to give way to reason (for he was a knowledgeable man) and let go of his unrequited love for Esmeralda.\r\n\r\nMaybe Loki (Marvel Universe) accepts his fate as an adopted brother and rather helps Thor in the safekeeping of Asgard.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.despicablemegames.info/games/images/18-despicable-me-2-animation-movie.jpg" alt="" width="557" height="348" />\r\n\r\nThis is where our imagination and expectations go wild, fellow readers.\r\n\r\n6. Psychos are entertaining. :)\r\n\r\nThere are some villains who capture our hearts but there are some who are simply blood-curdling and we love every second of it.\r\n\r\nChristoph Waltz as SS Colonel Hans Landa (Inglorious Basterds) was horrifying and brilliant.\r\n\r\nAmerican Psycho is now generated as academic work because of Christian Bale''s smooth transitions as a man of great reputation to a psychotic serial killer.\r\n\r\nAlso, how can one forget the loathsome woman in pink, Dolores Umbridge or Cruella De Vil.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500.gif"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-250 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500-300x181.gif" alt="tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500" width="300" height="181" /></a>\r\n\r\n7. (Bonus reason) A good looking villain is like icing on a cake.\r\n\r\nWith the slyness of a fox and the looks of an angel, our hearts turn into a frenzy of hate and passion. We would gladly give into the dark side if they were the villain of our story. ;)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class="" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/original/11113/111136107/3993372-8788862310-dexte.jpg" alt="" width="302" height="227" /><img id="irc_mi" class=" alignright" src="http://vignette2.wikia.nocookie.net/marvelmovies/images/a/ae/Mystique_2000.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20130813004115" alt="" width="191" height="258" />', 'Behind the Facade of Villainy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'behind-the-facade-of-villainy', '', '', '2015-06-24 19:45:03', '2015-06-24 14:15:03', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=247', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(214, 8, '2015-06-03 20:48:32', '2015-06-03 15:18:32', 'Which is your favourite Roald Dahl book?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/author_dahl.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-215" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/author_dahl-234x300.jpg" alt="author_dahl" width="234" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nA routine enough question for any person who wandered into this wonderful word at an early age.\r\nMost of the answers are the same, Charlie and The Chocolate Factory,\r\nThe tale of a young and simple boy bought up in a family of meager means who receives the biggest surprise of a child''s life when he finds a golden ticket which is the pass for the world''s biggest chocolate factory owned by the great Willy Wonka.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-216" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download-2.jpg" alt="download (2)" width="183" height="276" /></a>\r\n\r\nIt had everything that delighted children,\r\nChocolate of all sizes and kinds possible, People of all sizes and kinds possible, Silly Limericks and a nice boy.\r\nBut, I never found this book appealing, and when people told me that this was Roald Dahl''s best work, I was disappointed.\r\n\r\nBut as luck would have it, I found this book which had a scrawny girl standing on a pile of books on its cover at Crossword(Kudos, you amazing place!). Matilda, the title read, and that first flip, to the page that contained the primary illustrations, was the beginning to what has been a lifelong obsession with knowledge and information.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-217" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download.jpg" alt="download" width="188" height="267" /></a>\r\n\r\nMatilda is a little girl who is far too good to be true. At age five-and-a-half she''s knocking off double-digit multiplication problems and blitz-reading Dickens. Even more remarkably, her classmates love her even though she''s a super-nerd and the teacher''s pet. But everything is not perfect in Matilda''s world. For starters she has two of the most idiotic, self-centered parents who ever lived. Then there''s the large, busty nightmare of a school principal, Mrs. ("The") Trunchbull, a former hammer-throwing champion who flings children at will and is approximately as sympathetic as a bulldozer.\r\nShe warms up with some practical jokes aimed at her hapless parents, but the true test comes when she rallies in defense of her teacher, the sweet Miss Honey, against the diabolical Trunchbull. There is never any doubt that Matilda will carry the day. Even so, this wonderful story is far from predictable.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-218" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images.jpg" alt="images" width="276" height="182" /></a>\r\n\r\nMatilda is the only children’s book I still relate to, it spoke about a girl with an unquenchable thirst for knowledge who let no circumstance or obstacle impede her from fulfilling her desire. It made books the best source for information rather than the Internet and taught me a lesson that has proved right again and again, almost like a buoy, anchoring me to my childhood sans a smartphone. It taught me that the best kind of pleasure is gained when two covers of plastic encapsulate a clump of pages, not when a screen glued to some circuit boards is surrounded by our fingers, thus propping it up to burn out the cornea.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-219" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/download-1.jpg" alt="download (1)" width="275" height="183" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI end with the parting note the man always used, as a child I could only picture a candle, never understanding the meaning of it.\r\n\r\n<strong>"My candle burns at both ends It will not last the night But ah my foes and ah my friends It gives a lovely light"</strong>\r\n\r\nNow, thanks to Matilda, not knowing something is a thing of the past.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'My Youngest Hero(ine)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'my-youngest-heroine', '', '', '2015-06-03 20:48:32', '2015-06-03 15:18:32', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=214', 0, 'post', '', 0),
