nt-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Or the science gathered among the pages </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">And these words bring people together </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Language unites and sets us free </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">But it is same words that bind us </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">As when two different cultures meet. </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;', 'The Story of Words', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '222-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-06 23:04:11', '2015-06-06 17:34:11', '', 222, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/222-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(236, 2, '2015-06-20 19:36:14', '2015-06-20 14:06:14', 'A teacher asked one of her kindergarten students what he thought was his greatest milestone in life yet. Simply out of curiosity. The child answered, “What is a m..mile..milestone?” The teacher smiled and explained, “A milestone is an important event in someone’s life. Like when you turn ten years old or when you go to college!” The child thought for a minute and said, “My dad got me my first basketball yesterday. I think that was an important event in my life.”\r\n\r\nA son asked his father, what to him was his life’s most cherished milestone. “There are many”, the father said, “but the day I married your mother has been my most favourite ever since.”\r\n\r\nA friend asked her 38-year old, National Award winning Kathak teacher, what her single most important milestone in life was. She said, “I beat Cancer. Twice.”\r\n\r\nMy sister told me a few days ago that I must go out for drinks with her whenever I would visit her next. I asked her if she would be willing to look out for me if I went about hurling everywhere after. “Yes!”, she said. “Those are milestones too.”\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images1111.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-241 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images1111.jpg" alt="images111" width="276" height="183" /></a>\r\n\r\nEach of us, no matter how old we are or where we come from, has a list of things that we might have achieved or are hopeful about achieving. When we strike out some things off that list, we call them milestones- things that remind us how far we have come, the things we witnessed on the way, the sacrifices we made to get where we are, and all that lies ahead.\r\n\r\nOne year is a long time. 365 days, 8,760 hours, 52,56,000 minutes and 3,15,36,000 seconds. Every moment is a new memory made. Every breath, every step, every sigh, every thought, every blink of the eye, every sight- is unique in its own way. When we put these elements in a string together, the multidimensional image of our one by gone year emerges.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-6.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-239 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-6.jpg" alt="images (6)" width="275" height="183" /></a>\r\n\r\nOne year since you found your soul mate, one year since you got that car you had been saving all your life for, one year since you took that trip with your best friends, one year since your brother started attending school, one year since your dog passed away after having lived a long and healthy life, one year since your twins turned one, one year since that house got burned down, one year since you moved to a new continent, one year since you made a million new memories, since you shed a few tears, since you laughed so hard you could feel the pressure in your head- one year since you lived.\r\n\r\nThe past year has been special to the team of The Book Hub too. I asked the Owner-Developer to tell me how it all started. He said, “<em>Main bore ho raha tha. Mere paas bohot saari e-books padi thien. Sabko ek jagah upload kiya aur chaar pages ki website bana daali!</em>” (When I started out, I only did it to avoid getting bored. I had a lot of e-books, so I uploaded them at one place and created a four-page long website.) I was amazed, and to be honest, slightly disappointed. I was looking for something more solid, deep and meaningful behind the making of this website. And all I was given was “<em>boriyat</em>” (boredom). This was exactly when it struck me that we keep waiting for good things to shape up amidst much pomp and show while forgetting to realise that “life is what happens to us when we are busy making plans”, that life’s most magnificent pleasures are hidden away in the simplest folds of its fabric.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-7.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-238 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-7.jpg" alt="images (7)" width="267" height="189" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Book Hub began with a handful of college-going kids, brought together by the shared passion for books and a deep-seated interest in technology. And here we are- 365 days, 15,000 visitors (and counting) and with an outreach to over 20 countries later- celebrating our first milestone; growing slowly, yet steadily. So imperative and valuable are these events- those that have kept so many of us going; that gave us a reason to start afresh, to keep trying our hands at what we want to do, to bridge the gap between where we are and where we want to be, to believe in the miracle that is human life.\r\n\r\nI am reminded of something Shri Shri Ranbir Kapoorji said in one of his motion pictures that aids my purpose here, “<em>Kahin par pohonchane ke liye, kahin se nikalna bohot zaroori hota hai!</em>” (In order to get somewhere, it is necessary that we get away from somewhere!). Rightfully so. How do we plan on achieving another milestone otherwise, right?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2.jpg"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-237 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2-300x206.jpg" alt="2" width="300" height="206" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: center">Well, we turned one today and it is almost surreal. We feel ‘one’derful!</p>', 'The Journey To The Milestone', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-journey-to-the-milestone', '', '', '2015-06-21 12:29:20', '2015-06-21 06:59:20', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=236', 0, 'post', '', 10),
