(52, 2, '2015-03-28 20:53:54', '2015-03-28 15:23:54', '<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG-20150328-WA0020.jpg">\n</a>People, over the years, have devised unique ways of expressing their thoughts and opinions. In recent times, technological development has furthered that ability in us. That is not to say persons from generations by gone were any less innovative. It is a tendency in humans to find solace in being able to relate with someone who has similar ideas as themselves. We enjoy reading what others might have to say only to polish our own approach towards the subject in question. So, through these ingenious methods such as the print media- newspapers, magazines, novels and comics among several others- we have engineered a way to communicate with the world at large, perhaps, even the anonymous.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nChildhood is a time that most of us remember fondly, for being carefree and nonchalant did not have severe ramifications back then. More so, because of the memories we made doing what we loved. Learning our first letters and words marked our respective beginnings into the real world. The relationship that was crafted between us and the alphabet saw newer highs, escalating from picture books in kindergarten to comics as growing kids.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nComics are means to share mental reflections of things we see around us everyday with the help of text and pictures put together in one capsule. Panels of images adorned with cartoons became the most celebrated form of comic illustrations. This concept flourished primarily in Western Europe, the United States and Japan. <em>The Adventures of Tintin</em> by Georges Remi popularised comic strips in Western Europe. American comics developed in the early 20<sup>th</sup> century primarily through Richard Outcault’s <em>The Yellow Kid</em>.The endeavor was predominated by humour initially but eventually drama, satire and adventure too began to gain momentum among readers. Periodic comic books first appeared in the 1930s and the <em>Superman</em> by Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster marked the beginning of a new era in the field.<em> Tarzan</em> by Harold Foster, <em>Dick Tracey </em>by Chester Gould, <em>Dennis the Menace</em> by Hank Ketcham, <em>Peanuts</em> by Charles Schulz, <em>Archie Comics</em> and <em>Walt Disney</em> cartoon strips are outstanding examples for the same. Also, let us not forget our very own <em>Chacha Chaudhary </em>taking the nation by storm since 1971.\n\n<img class=" aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/IMG-20150328-WA0020-300x98.jpg" alt="IMG-20150328-WA0020" width="562" height="184" />\n\nComic books were probably our first sincere efforts as kids to nurture a habit of reading. If we try and walk down memory lane, I am certain all of us will find our younger selves hiding a comic in an open textbook as we pretended to study! Comics encouraged our fragile minds to take that flight of imagination on an adventurous trip, marking a departure from our humdrum lives. Reading them, we could be anybody and we could do anything. They rescued us from the monotony of homework and tests. Exchanging our lot with that of our friends was a serious agenda during the summer break. Interestingly, comics served the varying tastes of kids and adults alike, making it a recollection we share with our parents(especially our fathers!). I remember biting my nails over <em>Tintin</em>; and wondering what the <em>Archie-Veronica-Betty </em>triangle would lead to; and how I could be a menace for my then annoying neighbours.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nTimes, however, have changed. In a world that is in the clutches of the internet and social media, much of what a regular 90’s kid thrived on is now a foreign concept for  the kids of present times. Comics have lost their magic and charm. The characters and plots have been borrowed and transformed into cartoon series and motion pictures to cater to a wider audience. And rightfully so. But the experience of reading one’s favourite comics and visualising oneself as one of the characters-things that were a testimony to our innocence and our out worldly fancies- have become the talk of the past. Even for those of us who loved reading comic books, swinging back to them has become extremely unlikely, owing to changing inclination towards novels and also because of our erratic lifestyles.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nEven so, I would like to believe that there is a part in all of us that is, to this day, fascinated with the things we pursued years ago, a part that wants to be a kid once again, a part that wants to escape life’s drudgeries, a part that yearns for a ‘blast from the past’. Don''t you ever feel like taking a peek into your good old days? If yes, walking up to that book shelf to look for a comic book that might be lying around somewhere might not be that bad an idea after all.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSo, this Sunday?', 'Comics: A Blast From The Past', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-03-28 20:53:54', '2015-03-28 15:23:54', '', 49, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/49-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
