r to a wider audience. And rightfully so. But the experience of reading one’s favourite comics and visualising oneself as one of the characters-things that were a testimony to our innocence and our out worldly fancies- have become the talk of the past. Even for those of us who loved reading comic books, swinging back to them has become extremely unlikely, owing to changing inclination towards novels and also because of our erratic lifestyles.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEven so, I would like to believe that there is a part in all of us that is, to this day, fascinated with the things we pursued years ago, a part that wants to be a kid once again, a part that wants to escape life’s drudgeries, a part that yearns for a ‘blast from the past’. Don''t you ever feel like taking a peek into your good old days? If yes, walking up to that book shelf to look for a comic book that might be lying around somewhere might not be that bad an idea after all.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, this Sunday?', 'Comics: A Blast From The Past', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '49-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-03-28 20:54:12', '2015-03-28 15:24:12', '', 49, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/49-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(102, 1, '2015-04-11 19:19:03', '2015-04-11 13:49:03', 'In the ‘Harry Potter’ series, how much do we actually focus on the one crucial character who had almost escaped having Harry’s fate just because he was born one day earlier than Harry? Who handled Snape’s wrath because if Lord Voldemort had gone for him, Lily would’ve survived? Who had his parents tortured to insanity by Bellatrix Lestrange and the damage was so strong his mother didn’t recognize him and he lived in burning hell everyday knowing that he would never have the same connection with them that he had before? We may not accept it but living a life knowing your parents don’t know you is a fate worse than being dead. Sorry Harry but at least you know your parents would know you if they were alive. Neville Longbottom has our sympathy here *I don’t mean to be rude people* Let’s give it up to Neville’s true Gryffindor personality!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville1.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville1-300x155.jpg" alt="hp-neville" width="300" height="155" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-92" /></a>\r\n\r\nNevilleLongbottom is that one important character who literally determines the whole course of series. He could’ve easily been ‘The Chosen One’, allowing Harry to be a normal wizard boy on ‘The Hogwarts Express’ without a scar, sitting with other kids, laughing without worries. But destiny had different plans for him. He did land up with scars, psychological ones, a little more painful than Harry’s. He has quite a lot of followers and fans in the fandom and who can blame him?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/download.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/download.jpg" alt="download" width="194" height="260" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-84" /></a>\r\n\r\nNot to forget his excruciatingly painful and good looks, he’s got the soul and qualities of a true Gryffindor – humility, nobility, kindness, loyalty, fierce supportiveness and bravery. Neville is a crystal clear reflection of the ‘real-life- Gryffindors, who have a potential to be true heroes under the most dangerous and life threatening situations, but not be a ‘Superman’ while sleeping and waking up. He clearly understands that being a person isn’t about being ‘the one’ who is always noticed no matter where they go and thrashing up villains at every freaking chance they get (No offence Harry, but Neville has his own points and you know it), it’s about deciding your battles and know what’s close enough to your heart and worth fighting for. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville3.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville3-300x168.jpg" alt="hp-neville3" width="300" height="168" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-85" /></a>\r\n\r\nNeville could’ve easily gotten Harry’s life by a span of one SINGLE DAY, has Voldemort seen him as a ‘real threat’ and let Harry live a little more normally.\r\nNow if we try to clearly dig into a little research, J K. Rowling has actually drawn Neville’s character from someone parallel in the previous generation: The Marauders. She did this with a lot of thinking, taking into account other characters. Neville is (please don’t kill ME) Peter Pettigrew. Okay! I’ll take the hurl of swear words till your actually understand why this was observed. He is the one who usually tags along with the trio but is looked down upon by everyone as he’s not remarkably talented or suave. He’s like the priest who knows every one of Harry’s most important secrets and could easily spill the beans. But then AGAIN! He’s a truly loyal Gryffindor! In addition, Professor McGonagall calls Peter Pettigrew ‘foolish boy’. Just like him Neville is another pureblood who has technically no respect from the notable wizarding families. Neville is the kid everyone picks on when Harry, Ron and Hermione aren’t around to defend him; gullible and the easy mark. He could’ve been Peter’s brand new analog in the story. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-peter.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-peter-300x164.jpg" alt="hp-peter" width="300" height="164" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-86" /></a>\r\n\r\nReason being – he can either ruin a dish or make it the epitome of perfection. He’s the game changer, tide turner and the shiny hinge. (whatever you want to call him) Apart from this, he’s in the same position as Wormtail, who made all the hard choices Wormtail didn’t. Of all the characters, Neville is the only one who goes the furthest to prove that an individual’s destiny is in his hands.  He of course, possesses other characteristics worth talking about, other than his own. What is important here is how his strengths fill in group dynamics needed by the Marauders. He’s wanted by the trio the same way Lily, James and the Order of Phoenix wanted Peter. Just that Neville is more than upto the task.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville2.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville2-300x161.jpg" alt="hp-neville2" width="300" height="161" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-87" /></a> \r\n\r\nNeville teaches us a lesson in self-worth and shows us that having a strong personality doesn''t always mean that  you''re meant to lead people and will only make the right decisions. Society at large only sees the leaders and their closest friends are dismissed at the first glance, pretty much like Neville was dismissed by his classmates in the first year. However, he doesn’t let his peers’ attitude affect him enough to give up. Instead, over the years. His self-depreciation turns into persistent desire to improve and increase his skill set on offering help irrespective of its need and he figures out how he can best come of use in a fight.\r\nHis very first act of heroism is seen in ‘Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone’ when he stands up to Harry, Ron and Hermione, becoming a victim to Hermione’s full ‘Body Bind’ curse which gives him enough points for Gryffindor to win the house Cup. He personally makes sure to announce Neville’s name at the last so as to make Neville proud of his bravery to stand up against his friends when he was right. (given that Dumbledore was actually scared that history would repeat itself and he was more than relieved that Neville chose a different road) Immediately after that incident, he avoids falling into Peter’s shoes by stepping away a little from the trio so that it showed people that his meekness isn’t a signal for people to mess around with him.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-3.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-3.jpg" alt="images (3)" width="276" height="183" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-94" /></a>\r\n\r\nHe’s the defender, the keeper of hope and a true friend. When Harry publicly claims to see Lord Voldemort in the fourth year, the world speculates and calls him a liar, making a mockery out of him. Neville however, sticks to his side and believes him, fighting with him unlike most who run away and pee in their pants when real danger comes. He keeps the alive the ‘Dumbledore’s Army’ in Hogwarts despite Harry’s absence. He assumes the leader’s role, which was the hardest job anyone could do given Snape was the Headmaster during that time and builds a refuge in the ‘Room of Requirement’. Despite witnessing the murders, tortures and kidnappings of his closest friends, he stays hopeful in the castle, hopefully waiting for Harry, Ron and Hermione to return. He’s the PRIME FACTOR for the ‘Battle of Hogwarts’ to take place. We can’t deny he was the spark that set the castle on fire. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville5.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville5-300x159.jpg" alt="hp-neville5" width="300" height="159" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-89" /></a>\r\n\r\nLeaving all this aside, Neville doesn’t fail his parents as the perfect son. Neville’s bravery, strength and love for his family keeps him fighting on for them even though they’re no longer there. He makes it his goal to be that ideal son though his parents would never know of his feats, deeds and mark in the wizarding world. \r\nIn the final hour, fate is about to make history repeat itself when he’s given the same cowardly choice of joining Voldemort and taking the easy way out. He changes the game at that very moment by drawing the sword of Gryffindor out of the burning Sorting Hat and slicing off Nagini’s head, ending Voldemort’s life. This moment proves that Harry needs Neville just the way he needs Ron and Hermione to end the war and put a cork in the bottle. It all comes down to Neville – the boy who demanded respect from his friends at the very start no matter how he felt and he chose to do what was right because it was the hardest thing to do.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/downloadii.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/downloadii.jpg" alt="downloadii" width="271" height="186" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-93" /></a>\r\n\r\nNow that we actually observe Neville under a whole new light, we discover that he’s indeed, the truest of Gryffindors and balances the entire HP narrative. Which makes us think – what would’ve Peter Pettigrew been like if he had known that courage wasn’t about following blindly following someone but about choosing to do what was right even when nobody asked that of you. He taught us that in this huge world filled with people who blend in easily with the crowd  and are followed because they’re known, there are some people who may seem different and ‘out of place’ but sometimes, THEY are the ones who lead the world to a better future……\r\nHere are 3 whole pages, OUR tribute to the truest Gryffindor – Neville Longbottom ‘The Boy who Could’ve Been’ and ‘The Boy who Made History’\r\n#SaluteToNevilleLongbottom !\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-4.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-4.jpg" alt="images (4)" width="184" height="273" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-95" /></a>\r\n', 'The Game changer and truest Gryffindor', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '91-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-11 19:19:03', '2015-04-11 13:49:03', '', 91, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/91-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
