(60, 1, '2015-04-03 22:52:36', '2015-04-03 17:22:36', 'There’s no easy way to start on a specific point about books. A good book is the ultimate muse for a reader.\r\n\r\nSuch is their magic. Those stacks of pages filled with stories, experiences and tales in attractive covers are like gateways to a beautiful world of imagination where anyone can be what they want without being judged, mocked or instructed. An alternate universe into which eager readers slip to find themselves in the exotic worlds of their abstract minds.\r\n\r\nIt all starts with turning the first page of that treasure trove of indelible expressions: narration and connection which holds the reader close and engages the mind into an unforgettable literary adventure. The feel of a new book, smell of fresh pages, color of a new front cover and sight of the title to a reader is like a flower to a honeybee. Words wait to cast their spell on people. The ultimate fantasy of any reader is to either own an unbelievably big library at some point in their lives or sit in one corner of anywhere with a beverage, munchies and a good book.\r\n\r\nBooks have come a long way from illustrations, journals, autobiographies, testimonies, novels and who knows where this might all go. Reading is like a therapy and a good book is a vacation you need if you really want a break without troubling your pockets. Bonus points of reading – good reading habits, richer vocabulary with a better understanding of the language,  healthy mind exercise, getting a better chance to understand what the readers want and more knowledge.\r\n\r\nQuoting the iconic J.K. Rowling, “I don’t believe in magic. But words are, in my not-so-humble opinion, our most inexhaustible source of magic.” We really can’t argue with that now, can we?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/book-2.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/book-2.jpg" alt="book 2" width="290" height="174" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe also know authors and writers who have spun magic with their words over the decades. To name a few renowned literary legends, there’s Jeffrey Archer, Dan Brown,  J. K. Rowling ( again), Ruskin Bond, Ayn Rand and Daniel Defoe.  Now let’s talk about the most common mistake we often make as readers – confusing writers with authors. Authors are the ones who create and invent plots and are the originators of ideas. Writers are the ones focusing on one idea and modifying it to suit their storyline. It’s more like a sub-class of the main class.\r\nTo add to it, books are like best friends – they never leave you no matter what. Reading a book is like preparing yourself to be strapped to a roller-coaster of emotions. It’s like reading an untold life story, discovering an exotic land, unraveling a mystery, knowing an unshared experience. It’s not always easy to pick up a book, but once you do it, it’s pretty much worth it. Also, reading books may have one of these outcomes (maybe even multiple):\r\n•	Sometimes, the story leaves such an impression on your life, your mind just hangs in there and ponders over what you just read. Great stories rarely come by and when that happens, it’ll be days before the reader’s mind is fresh enough to go on another literary adventure.\r\n•	Chances are the writer has taken a good idea and not done such a good job elaborating on it (Let’s face it! Everyone’s not good with ideas and expression). However, one bad book can help potential writers understand the Do’s and Don’ts of producing some real good reading material.\r\n•	At times, the engaging factors for the reader are the characters, their personalities and the way they handle the world. Intimate connection with characters is a common occurrence and this may result in them playing a big role to mould the reader into a person. So, yeah you could say the readers are in a big way affected by what kind of stories they read.\r\n•	This clause may be fatal if one is a hard-core reader (chuckles softly): Some books often have characters and storylines that are somehow deeply connected with how the real world is. The reader develops a strong affection for the characters and more than often sees them as a second family. They can relate to the fictional individuals and try to understand the situation they are in. This way, the story becomes an integral part of the reader’s life, giving him/her life lessons, countless memories and in some cases, a childhood. \r\n•	Books also have a big role in determining how the reader might end up looking at the world and behave accordingly. This you could say, is something like ‘temporary inspiration’. The plot could be so overpowering that for some time the reader could actually try and imitate the fictional individuals expecting the same outcome as in the book. Books, as we don’t usually expect, have a technical aspect too. They’re more than just words and language; intricately linked with our lives and understanding of what’s happening around us.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg" alt="books" width="274" height="184" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-61" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe best part about them is – they don’t manipulate you. It’s a free world where you can venture off wherever your heart and mind lead you. A world which you can carry along with you everywhere. ‘Books are knowledge’ isn’t a fashion statement. It’s pretty much valid because some of them are authored or written by people who actually cement their storyline with some research to blend in fiction and reality. It’s like taking the reader on an imaginary tour yet keeping him within the real world. We can’t even say it’s not true.\r\n\r\nAlso, books are a more intimate form of expression since time immemorial. Over here, I’m actually talking about the hard-copies. There’s a strange love that only a true book-lover can understand when one gets to touch the book in all its dimensions. Technology and e-books can never replace real books that way. Tactility is something that helps the reader build a connection with what he’s about to read, according to psychological studies, it stimulates his curiosity as humans respond and react mostly to touch. \r\n\r\nBooks also have a crucial role in forming a person’s mindset. For instance: a person indulging way too often in fiction may end up being way too imaginative and mentally immature. Romance novels often make the reader develop the notion that love is a beautiful feeling (which it is, no doubt) but they may also cause the reader that love stories have a perfectly happy ending as usually portrayed in books. It could cause the person to mistake ‘like’ for ‘love’ and fall in love with the ‘concept of love’. It is amazing no doubt but one should always balance out the proportion in which he/she reads every genre, that’s the moral. (All said from personal experience)\r\n\r\nAlso, most importantly, books are an invaluable medium of communication. Talking and reaching out to people, sending across your views, opinions, stories and ideas with feedback in the form of critic’s review and the readership.  Apart from this, when people read, it surely raises some questions, which makes them interact with others who have read the same book. Interaction leads to bonding and it goes on.\r\n\r\nLooking at all this, we could reiterate the fact that books have more than just one aspect; social, personal, psychological and technical. An in-depth understanding of everything above would help us realize exactly how important are books in our lives. \r\nFor these very reasons, books are invaluable treasures for mankind that not only need to be preserved but also promoted, loved and respected. They are beautiful gifts that deserve to be cherished, beating hearts of book-lovers.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, I would end with a well known saying,\r\n“They say humans only live one life, but a reader has already lived a billion.”<strong></strong> <a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1-300x200.jpg" alt="books 1" width="300" height="200" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-64" /></a>\r\n', 'More than just ''Books''', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'more-than-just-books', '', '', '2015-04-03 23:04:20', '2015-04-03 17:34:20', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=60', 0, 'post', '', 0),
