y. They can relate to the fictional individuals and try to understand the situation they are in. This way, the story becomes an integral part of the reader’s life, giving him/her life lessons, countless memories and in some cases, a childhood. \r\n•	Books also have a big role in determining how the reader might end up looking at the world and behave accordingly. This you could say, is something like ‘temporary inspiration’. The plot could be so overpowering that for some time the reader could actually try and imitate the fictional individuals expecting the same outcome as in the book. Books, as we don’t usually expect, have a technical aspect too. They’re more than just words and language; intricately linked with our lives and understanding of what’s happening around us.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg" alt="books" width="274" height="184" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-61" /></a>\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1-300x200.jpg" alt="books 1" width="300" height="200" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-64" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe best part about them is – they don’t manipulate you. It’s a free world where you can venture off wherever your heart and mind lead you. A world which you can carry along with you everywhere. ‘Books are knowledge’ isn’t a fashion statement. It’s pretty much valid because some of them are authored or written by people who actually cement their storyline with some research to blend in fiction and reality. It’s like taking the reader on an imaginary tour yet keeping him within the real world. We can’t even say it’s not true.\r\nAlso, books are a more intimate form of expression since time immemorial. Over here, I’m actually talking about the hard-copies. There’s a strange love that only a true book-lover can understand when one gets to touch the book in all its dimensions. Technology and e-books can never replace real books that way. Tactility is something that helps the reader build a connection with what he’s about to read, according to psychological studies, it stimulates his curiosity as humans respond and react mostly to touch. \r\nBooks also have a crucial role in forming a person’s mindset. For instance: a person indulging way too often in fiction may end up being way too imaginative and mentally immature. Romance novels often make the reader develop the notion that love is a beautiful feeling (which it is, no doubt) but they may also cause the reader that love stories have a perfectly happy ending as usually portrayed in books. It could cause the person to mistake ‘like’ for ‘love’ and fall in love with the ‘concept of love’. It is amazing no doubt but one should always balance out the proportion in which he/she reads every genre, that’s the moral. (All said from personal experience)\r\nAlso, most importantly, books are an invaluable medium of communication. Talking and reaching out to people, sending across your views, opinions, stories and ideas with feedback in the form of critic’s review and the readership.  Apart from this, when people read, it surely raises some questions, which makes them interact with others who have read the same book. Interaction leads to bonding and it goes on.\r\nLooking at all this, we could reiterate the fact that books have more than just one aspect; social, personal, psychological and technical. An in-depth understanding of everything above would help us realize exactly how important are books in our lives. \r\nFor these very reasons, books are invaluable treasures for mankind that not only need to be preserved but also promoted, loved and respected. They are beautiful gifts that deserve to be cherished, beating hearts of book-lovers.\r\nIn conclusion, I would end with a well known saying,\r\n“They say humans only live one life, but a reader has already lived a billion.”<strong></strong>', 'More than just ''Books''', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-03 22:48:22', '2015-04-03 17:18:22', '', 60, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/60-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
