(230, 1, '2015-06-10 20:21:39', '2015-06-10 14:51:39', '<em>''Th</em><em>at night I realized what all authors and writers go through. The moment I  penned the last word of my story, I felt satisfied knowing that I had done justice to the characters of my story. It was a beautiful feeling. But then, my heart broke knowing that I had to bid goodbye to them.Though it wasn''t really a goodbye.''</em>\r\n\r\nHonestly, I wasn''t intending on writing what I''m going to write at this moment. My first thought was, ''I had an exhilarating experience. I can''t make a draft of it and then write it out. It''ll be better if I''m spontaneous.''\r\n\r\nHere I am.\r\n\r\nI looked at myself in the mirror. My eyes resembled those of Lord Voldemort - scarlet red. Yes, they were tired and looked bloodshot after the period of time I spent trying to figure out the character and personality of my story''s protagonist. It had been a good number of two hours and till now I just knew that my protagonist was a 15 year old girl who had cancer and then my thoughts trailed off into a fading train of words as my eyes flitted to the half written page.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/images12_0-367x275.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nMy inspiration looked as bleak as a candle flame that was dying out. I had tobring it back before it went extinct. With full determination, I picked up my pen, refraining myself from looking at the time, for time meant nothing for me right now. I had a story to write.\r\n\r\nI happily toiled away and burnt the midnight oil. Occasionally, there was a violent outbreak in my mind when a chunk of ideas used to aggressively knock on the doors of my brain, trying to get in. With great difficulty, I turned a deaf ear to them, for I knew that ''too many cooks spoil a good broth.'' The most painful and crucial part was the game changer, the twist in the story. It''s never easy to decide how you want your story to go about, specially when you''re not sure of what''s going to happen next and also when you don''t know what kind of literature people like reading. There are so many different tastes and preferences but just one story.\r\n\r\n''Pen down the first scenario that comes to the mind'' - that was the easiest strategy I planned to adopt. I am no pro at writing but only an emerging writer. I had to give this piece a lovely form with the simplest ideas. I had to give my characters the closure they needed. My characters were like my children, my own family and I couldn''t abandon them on some random page of a diary!\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/family_1-347x257.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIn sometime I realized my growing attachment to my newly found family that I had discovered in the hidden corners of my own mind. I found myself laughing, crying and rejoicing with them; protecting them from every destructive and masochistic thought that came to my mind. They were a part of me and hurting them would be like hurting myself.\r\n\r\nI was halfway through my story by then and I felt that this was one hell of a journey I had while writing one. Like a trip to a world from where I didn''t want to come back. I was free; to feel, do and say whatever I wanted to. It was beautiful and liberating with the right people. My creations were no less than people.\r\n\r\nHowever, this did include a big deal of mental dilemma, literary complications and ups and downs. Writing something is not a piece of cake, I assure you. You have to pick the right words. You can''t write something and turn it into something else. You have to know what you want and how you intend to go about it. You can''t lose track and then come back to write any nonsense just to make it a part of the work. It should make some sense.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/hotguy-443x295.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nWell, enough said, I snapped back to reality as I realized that the story was now nearing the climax. That''s what broke my heart. This had to end anyway. Sooner or later. They were going away from me. Yet another family was going to be preserved in the pages of my diary. Another lesson and wonderful experience with memories to cherish. Like a part of myself had latched onto those people I talked to but never seen. The pain ripped me apart. Into a million pieces.\r\n\r\nMaybe what Stephen King said was right after all.\r\n\r\n"JK Rowling created seven <em>Horcruxes</em>. She put a part of her soul in every book and now her books will live forever"\r\n\r\nI guess I did the same. But it was painful enough with just one story.\r\n\r\nThe essence of a story is different when it''s complete. It''s captivating. I could go on reading mine for hours and hours but not get bored. To make myself believe that the pain would subside and lie to my heart that it wasn''t over.\r\n\r\nA completed story is a wonder to behold.\r\n\r\n<strong>A beautiful heartbreak.</strong>', 'The beautiful heartbreak', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '229-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-10 20:21:39', '2015-06-10 14:51:39', '', 229, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/229-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(160, 8, '2015-05-09 21:28:47', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'It''s my sixth birthday. I''ve had a huge party. I come back home to a host of presents. There''s the usual chocolates, remote control cars and toys. But at the far end of the table, there is a huge cuboidal shaped gift. I walk up to it and rip off the wrapping paper. It''s a set of 24 books, The Complete Adventures of Noddy, it says on the cover of the box. I give it a passing glance and move on to play with my newfangled vehicles. The next day, I take out the first book and start reading it. It talks about a toy who makes his own way to Toyland, earns his living, has hilarious adventures with his friends. I finish it in two days and I start the second one. A month later, all the twenty four books have food stains all over it owing to my habit of reading at the dining table. Unlike my appetite for food, this hunger has grown to epic proportions. I check the name on the box and it says Enid Blyton, in an almost illegible squiggle. A day later, another set of books lies on my desk, it says ''The And other stories collection''.\nOver the next coming years, all the books I bought were written by one person. They were the only gifts I asked for, the only gifts that I''d look forward to opening.\n\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://media.ticketmaster.co.uk/tm/en-gb/dbimages/13053a.jpg" alt="" width="305" height="225" />\n\nBook by book, my vocabulary expanded and my ability to identify incorrect grammar was continuously polished to the point that bolts went off in my mind every time I heard or read incorrect English. My essays became increasingly imaginative as a result of the amount of travelling I did to Fairyland each evening. For once, my parents didn’t complain because of the positive impact Enid Blyton was having on my English scores in school.\n\n<img class="alignnone" src="https://xoxymoronsx.files.wordpress.com/2010/07/cimg2655.jpg" alt="" width="623" height="223" />\n\nI became a young sleuth when I read Secret Seven, I became a child, blessed by angels when I read The Book of Fairies, I became a circus boy travelling in a caravan, miles yonder when I read Mr. Galliano’s Circus. This was where she became the first wizard I had the pleasure of meeting, it wasn’t me reading the book but it was me, living in the lines, the magic world she had created.\n\n<img class="alignnone" src="https://encrypted-tbn1.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQUHxK8IdUm7_6eGsXtfLkkrLb-MizEn3VIwIIYZaChUD9XZ_rT" alt="" width="104" height="160" />\n\nWhat Enid Blyton did for me was teach me English in a way no school teacher could ever hope to. She would make up completely absurd scenarios and still find a way to connect them with a child/s life and in a way that was imbibed with ease. I owe it to her for being that Grammar Nazi I am today, for never having to study for a test or a pop quiz on this wonderful language and most importantly for instilling me a love for literature and everything in print so deep that to this date I cannot sleep without a book by my side.\n<img class="alignnone" src="https://encrypted-tbn2.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcS6RE-nqGi3cnf4I-Aa7vjxFm_VSBUAEJzQznvXgg8X78Klg1_E" alt="" width="224" height="224" />\n\nAnd even today, when a child comes up to me and asks me for a book to read, I slip him a book, a binding of pages having words written on them. But in reality, I’m slipping him a tiny bit of magic, a new teacher and a whole new world, branded in that indelible squiggle of hers.\n“I always felt there was a place for me in all the books I read because that was what fantasy and fiction had taught me,that I could belong anywhere and anytime. Because everything was possible.” – Enid Blyton\nThank you, for teaching me to belong.\n<img class="alignnone" src="https://encrypted-tbn2.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcQqWKu1oYmslPo9NXUlhK28buD3F3aeZhPLgGz4Fo9qCDIy2EXL" alt="" width="326" height="155" />', 'My First English Teacher', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2015-05-09 21:28:47', '2015-05-09 15:58:47', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=160', 0, 'post', '', 0),
