(248, 1, '2015-06-24 19:19:02', '2015-06-24 13:49:02', '"Hero or Villain?" is a frequent question that acts as conversation starter in social circles and people usually prefer the villain. It is a bit surprising, to say the least, that people would deliberately choose a character that is portrayed as vindictive, resentful and even criminal over someone who is amiable and righteous. \r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\nA memorable tale is always determined by its plot and more importantly, its characters. A thrilling chemistry between the antagonist and protagonist that leaves the audience at the edge of their seats is sure to be a blockbuster or a bestseller. But the best stories that are a class apart are those with a well-defined villain. \r\nSure, ultimately the hero saves the day but it''s the villain that steals the show. Here are a few reasons why the hated are really the most loved. \r\n\r\n1. There would be no story without a villain. \r\n\r\nOne can only appreciate the light once you see the darkness. A hero''s ''pristine nature'' can be shown if has a plan to foil and an anti-hero to defeat. They are rivals yet complementary to each other and a perfect plot. \r\n\r\n2. An engrossing back story.\r\n\r\nBehind their devilish schemes, heinous intentions and hardened personalities, lie a hundred secrets why villains turned into monsters. \r\n\r\nTake for example, Bill the Butcher (or William Cutting), the antagonist in Gangs of New York. Inspired by real life gangster William Poole, Bill was a violent man hell-bent on revenge against immigrants who were responsible for his father''s death. He was known for his moral code, his patriotism and sense of honour. Today he is famously remembered for his last words, "Thank God... I died a true American."\r\n\r\nHeathcliff (Wuthering Heights), an iconic villain in English literature is a character still yet to be fully understood even after a century of his existence. Born as a homeless orphan but sheltered and mentored by Mr. Earnshaw, Heathcliff, Heathcliff falls in love with Catherine Earnshaw who betrays their love and marries Edgar Linton, a man of better social and economic background. In a rage of vengeance and sadness, Heathcliff becomes a living nightmare in a gentleman''s disguise. \r\n\r\n3. Honestly, they''re smarter. \r\n\r\nThere''s nothing more appealing than cunning intellect and a cunning intellect is a villain''s forte. \r\n\r\nLight Yagami (Death Note) could control death and the supernatural. \r\n\r\nMaster Sinister (X-Men), a scientific genius could alter his human genome to be invulnerable and ageless. Also he resuscitated Apocalypse, carrier of the first mutant X-gene. That''s pretty damn smart, \r\n\r\nMrs. Eleanor Iselin (The Manchurian Candidate)  is a ruthless Communist agent who plans to take over America. Her cold blooded and domineering attitude towards even her husband and son and her ambition to succeed makes her one of the smartest villains of all time. \r\n\r\n4. People are attracted to imperfections. \r\n\r\nEveryone wants to be perfect but we''re not. Heroes on paper and screens are the closest depiction to perfection. They represent goodwill, selflessness and struggle. They represent silver linings. \r\n\r\nVillains are a realistic portrayal of mankind''s flaws, exaggerations of man''s sins. They are greedy (Shylock), ambitious (Macbeth), broken (Voldemort), vengeful (Maleficent) and desirable (Jennifer in Jennifer''s Body). There is raw, crass and unabashed emotion in a villain which makes a story all the more better. In the real world, there is no black and white but shades of grey. \r\n\r\n5.  We cling to the hope that they might change sides. \r\n\r\nContinuing from the previous point, we truly want to believe that a villain has a human heart and even though tortured can seek redemption, \r\n\r\nDr. Gru from the Despicable Me series is a classic example. From conniving to steal the moon to become a doting father of three is a complete and delightful change of character. \r\n\r\nMaybe Claude Frollo (The Hunchback of Notre Dame) could find it in his otherwise compassionate heart to give way to reason (for he was a knowledgeable man) and let go of his unrequited love for Esmeralda. \r\n\r\nMaybe Loki (Marvel Universe) accepts his fate as an adopted brother and rather helps Thor in the safekeeping of Asgard. \r\n\r\nThis is where our imagination and expectations go wild, fellow readers. \r\n\r\n6. Psychos are entertaining. :)\r\n\r\nThere are some villains who capture our hearts but there are some who are simply blood-curdling and we love every second of it. \r\n\r\nChristoph Waltz as SS Colonel Hans Landa (Inglorious Basterds) was horrifying and brilliant. \r\n\r\nAmerican Psycho is now generated as academic work because of Christian Bale''s smooth transitions as a man of great reputation to a psychotic serial killer. \r\n\r\nAlso, how can one forget the loathsome woman in pink, Dolores Umbridge. \r\n\r\n7. (Bonus reason) A good looking villain is like icing on a cake. \r\n\r\nWith the slyness of a fox and the looks of an angel, our hearts turn into a frenzy of hate and passion. We would gladly give into the dark side if they were the villain of our story. ;)', 'Behind the Facade of Villainy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '247-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-24 19:19:02', '2015-06-24 13:49:02', '', 247, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/247-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
